{\rtf1\ansi \deff0{\fonttbl{\f8\fswiss Arial;}}\margl1440\margr1440\pgnstart61\sectd\pgnrestart\pgnstarts61\footery1080{\header \pard\plain\qr MYARC ADVANCED BASIC\par }{\footer \pard\plain\qr     VERSION 4.0  DDI SOFTWARE  \chpgn A\par }\pard\qj \plain\f8\fs20 \par \par \par \par In Graphics(1,2) and (1,3) modes, the computer divides each pixel-row into 32 groups of 8 pixels each. (This is most obvious when you assign a background-color other than cyan or transparent.) The computer can assign 1 foreground-color and 1 background-color (from among the 16 available colors), to each 8-pixel group.\par \par Program The following program uses DRAWTO to create a pattern across the top of the screen.\par \par 100 CALL GRAPHICS(3)\par 110 CALL CLEAR\par 120 A=20::B=20\par 130 CALL DRAW(1,A,B,A,B)\par 140 FOR X=1 TO 10\par 150 B=B+20\par 160 CALL DRAWTO(1,A,B)\par 170 CALL DRAWTO(1,A+20,B-20)\par 180 CALL DRAWTO(1,A+20,B)\par 190 CALL DRAWTO(1,A,B-20)\par 200 NEXT X\par 210 GOTO 210\par (Press CLEAR to stop the program.)\par \par \par A new command or program statement  CALL PSET(X,Y) can be used to set starting point for DRAWTO.\par }
